THE ELECTRON'S "PROBABILITY CLOUD"

The Modern Understanding of Atomic Structure

• The atomic structure as understood in modern science is not the classical representation
• Not a tiny little particle orbiting around the nucleus in a very clean sort of way (like a planet around a sun)
• That's an outdated, old-fashioned way of representing it (good as a general illustration)

What Physicists Now Know

• Physicists now know that electrons exist more in what they term a "PROBABILITY CLOUD"
• You're never really sure exactly where the electron is
• It's whipping around so fast
• It's somewhere in this hazy cloud that surrounds the nucleus
• Somewhere in there are a bunch of electrons, but where they are, we don't know

The Measurement Problem

• You don't know where the electron is until you take a measurement and freeze where it is
• But then you don't really understand exactly what its path has been because you're freezing it into a static state
• When it's moving, you don't really know where it is at any given moment

The Direct Correlation to Negative Beliefs

• The electron is similar to negative beliefs in that it creates this sort of:
  - Ambiguous fuzzy cloud
  - Something you can't really get a grip on
• It fools you into thinking that there are certain things going on that are:
  - Really only probabilities
  - Really only potentials
  - Not really very solid at all

Until You Make an Observation/Definition

• Things remain uncertain until you yourself decide that you're going to take a particular idea, particular definition
• Taking a definition is the same thing as an observation or a measurement (scientifically speaking)
• In taking that perspective and taking that measurement, then you get what you designed the perspective for
• You get what you designed the measurement or the experiment for
• That's the result you get

How the Electron Exemplifies Negative Beliefs

The electron does exemplify and represent the way negative beliefs work:

• They're kind of fuzzy - you're not really sure what's going on
• They tend to hide in your unconscious mind
• They don't make it easy to find them
• So you won't let them go
• This is their way of perpetuating themselves:
  - Telling you lies
  - Telling you more lies
  - Using tools like FEAR to prevent you from finding them
• So they can continue to get you to believe that what they're telling you about you is true (when it's not)

